<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="logs-and-exponent-logarithmic-functions-and-graphs">
  <title>Logarithmic Functions and Their Graphs</title>

  <p>
    The inverse of a simple exponential function, <m>f(x)=b^x, b \gt 0, b \neq 1</m>, is called a <term>logarithmic function</term>.  The inverse of <m>f(x)=b^x</m> is symbolized as
    <me>f^{-1}(x)=\log_b(x)</me>
    which is read aloud as "f-inverse of x equals the log-base-b of x."
  </p>
  <p>
    Let's consider the function <m>f(x)=2^x</m> and its inverse <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m>.  Recall that if <m>(a,b)</m> is an ordered pair on <m>f</m>, then <m>(b,a)</m> is an ordered pair on <m>f^{-1}</m>. Several function values for <m>f</m> are shown in <xref ref="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-table-1">Figure</xref> and several function values for <m>f^{-1}</m> are shown in <xref ref="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-table-2">Figure</xref>
  </p>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

