  </sidebyside>

  <p>
    Let's observe that every ordered pair in <xref ref="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-table-2">Figure</xref> satisfies the <m>2^y=x</m>.  It follows that 
    <me>y=\log_2(x)\,\,\text{if and only if}\,\,2^y=x.</me>
    This relationship is explored in depth in the section about logarithms as exponents.  In the current context, the relationship is a direct result of the inverse function relationship between exponential and logarithmic functions.  For the function <m>f(x)=2^x</m>, the ordered pairs satisfy the equation <m>y=2^x</m>.  It immediately follows that the ordered pairs on <m>f^{-1}</m> satisfy the equation <m>2^y=x</m>.
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      Plots of both <m>f(x)=2^x</m> and <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m> are plotted in <xref ref="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-figure-1">Figure</xref> . The line <m>y=x</m> is also plotted to highlight the fact that the two functions are reflections of one another across that line.  Let's first notice that the range of <m>f(x)=2^x</m>, <m>(0,\infty)</m>, becomes the domain of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m>.  Similarly, the domain of <m>f(x)=2^x</m>, <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>, becomes the range of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-figure-1">
      <caption><m>\highlight{y=2^x}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\log_2(x)}</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          A graph of the functions <m>y=2^x</m> and <m>y=\log_2(x)</m>.  The dashed line <m>y=x</m> is also graphed.  The two functions are mirror images across the line <m>y=x</m>.  The function <m>y=2^x</m> is every increasing and concave up whereas the function <m>y=\log_2(x)</m> is everywhere concave down.  Every <m>y</m>-coordinate on the function <m>y=2^x</m> is positive whereas every <m>x</m>-coordinate on the function <m>y=\log_2(x)</m> is positive.  On the left side of the graph of <m>y=2^x</m> the <m>x</m>-axis acts as a horizontal asymptote whereas on the left side of the graph <m>y=\log_2(x)</m> the <m>y</m>-axis acts as a vertical asymptote.  As you look from left to right the function <m>y=2^x</m> starts out nearly horizontal and becomes more and more vertical whereas the function <m>y=\log_2(x)</m> starts out nearly vertical and becomes more and more horizontal.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                            xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                            ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                            xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                            ytick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                            minor xtick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9},
                            minor ytick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9}]
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-9.9:3.3,smooth] ({2^x},{x});
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-9.9:3.3,smooth,color=blue] {2^x};
              \addplot[secondarycurve,domain=-9.9:9.9,smooth,color=gray] {x};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    Additional properties of <m>f(x)=2^x</m> and their attendant properties of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m> are shown below.  Please note that these properties are true whenever the base, <m>b</m>, is greater than 1.  Note that the symbols <m>x \rightarrow 0^+</m> are read as "x approaches zero <em>from the right</em>."
  </p>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      Properties of <m>f(x)=2^x</m>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The domain is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The range is <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>f(0)=1</m>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow 0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow \infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
      
    <p>
      Properties of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The range is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The domain is <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>f^{-1}(1)=0</m>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow 0^+</m>, <m>y \rightarrow -\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow \infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

  </sidebyside>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      Plots of both <m>f(x)=0.5^x</m> and <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_{0.5}(x)</m> are plotted in <xref ref="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-figure-2">Figure</xref> . These shapes are representative of <m>y=b^x</m> and <m>y=\log_b(x)</m> whenever <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>.  The properties are summarized below.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="logarithmic-functions-and-graphs-figure-2">
      <caption><m>\highlight{y=0.5^x}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\log_{0.5}(x)}</m></caption>
      <image>
        <description>
          A graph of the functions <m>y=0.5^x</m> and <m>y=\log_0.5(x)</m>.  The dashed line <m>y=x</m> is also shown.  The two curves are mirror images across the line <m>y=x</m> and they intersect at the approximate point <m>(0.64,0.6)</m>.  Both functions are everywhere decreasing and concave up.  The function <m>y=0.5^x</m> lies entirely above the <m>x</m>-axis while the function <m>y=\log_0,5(x)</m> lies entirely to the right of the <m>y</m>-axis.  The function <m>y=0.5^x</m> starts out nearly vertical and flattens out as it moves left-to-right ultimately approaching the positive <m>x</m>axis in an asymptotic fashion.  The function <m>y=\log_05(x)</m> start out nearly vertical to the right of the positive <m>y</m>-axis which acts as a vertical asymptote.  The function then becomes more and more horizontal as it moves rightward.
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[
          \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                            xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                            ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                            xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                            ytick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                            minor xtick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9},
                            minor ytick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9}]
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-3.3:9.9,smooth] ({.5^x},{x});
              \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-3.3:9.9,smooth,color=blue] {.5^x};
              \addplot[secondarycurve,domain=-9.9:9.9,smooth,color=gray] {x};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </sidebyside>
  <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      Properties of <m>f(x)=0.5^x</m>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The domain is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The range is <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>f(0)=1</m>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow \infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow 0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
      
    <p>
      Properties of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_{0.5}(x)</m>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The range is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The domain is <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>f^{-1}(1)=0</m>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>, <m>y \rightarrow -\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As <m>x \rightarrow 0^+</m>, <m>y \rightarrow \infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

  </sidebyside>
  <p>
    One closing comment.  In the section about exponential functions and their graphs, it was discussed that on a graph of <m>f(x)=2^x</m>, with a scale of inches on each axis, before <m>x</m> even gets to three feet, the value of <m>y</m> has already passed the moon.  That means that on a similarly scaled graph of <m>f^{-1}(x)=\log_2(x)</m>, <m>x</m> will have to extend beyond the moon before the corresponding value of <m>y</m> will even get three feet off the ground!  So while the range of <m>y=\log_2(x)</m> is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>, the spectacularly slow pace at which the function increases as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> makes the upper "limit" of the range somewhat misleading.
  </p>

